item.title: [JDK-8322809] SystemModulesMap::classNames and moduleNames arrays do not match the order
item.description:
A DESCRIPTION OF THE PROBLEM :
I have a java-project that is build as module. The name of the module starts with "com" (e.g. com.project). This module has a dependency to jdk.httpserver. When I run the compiled jar with java command, then everything works fine. But when I build a runtime image with jlink and try to start that one, I get an error ("Module com.project not in boot Layer").
If I change the module name to not start with "com" (e.g. org.project) or remove the dependency to jdk.httpserver or use Java 17, then the runtime image created by jlink works fine.

REGRESSION : Last worked in version 17.0.9

STEPS TO FOLLOW TO REPRODUCE THE PROBLEM :
Create a java project with a starter class (com.project.Starter) containing the main method.
Add module-info.java and name your project "com.project" and add dependency to "jdk.httpserver".
Compile the project.
Use jlink to build a runtime image:
jlink --module-path "c:\<path-to-jdk>\jmods;out" --add-modules com.project --launcher starter=com.project/com.project.Starter --output image

Execute image/bin/starter.bat and you will get an exception: "Module com.project not in boot Layer"

EXPECTED VERSUS ACTUAL BEHAVIOR :
EXPECTED -
Running application (no exception)
ACTUAL -
java.lang.InternalError: Module com.project not in boot Layer

---------- BEGIN SOURCE ----------
##Starter##
package com.project;

public class Starter {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("Hello world");
    }
}

##module-info.java##
module com.project {
    requires jdk.httpserver;
}
---------- END SOURCE ----------

CUSTOMER SUBMITTED WORKAROUND :
renaming module to not start with "com"

FREQUENCY : always

This bug exists since JDK 9. jdk.httpserver is the first JDK module created with ModuleMainClass attribute in JDK 18 that causes this issue to surface.

I think I understand the issue now. The SystemModulesPlugin (in method genSystemModulesMapClass) generates SystemModulesMap but it sorts the array of module names and separately sorts the array of class names to go into the generated arrays. This messes up the map when there is more than one module in the image with a main class. In the reproducer, there are two modules with main classes, the module "com.project" is being mapped to the SystemModules class generated for jdk.httpserver and vice versa. It looks like this issue may go back to JDK 9.

Thanks for the reproducer. For each module with the ModuleMainClass attribute, jlink is supposed to generate a SystemModules class, and a SystemModulesMap that maps the main module name to the class file. In this case, "com.project" maps to SystemModules$0 but this doesn't have module com.project, this triggers the exception at run-time. More digging needed to understand how this broken in JDK 18, it suggests we are missing test coverage. It can be worked around by running with --add-modules ALL-SYSTEM.

Information from submitter
-------------------
The error also occur in Java18. And I see this entry in the release notes of Java 18:

JEP 408: Simple Web Server
jwebserver, a command-line tool to start a minimal static web server, has been introduced. The tool and the accompanying API are located in the com.sun.net.httpserver package of the jdk.httpserver module and are designed to be used for prototyping, ad-hoc coding, and testing, particularly in educational contexts.
https://bugs.openjdk.org/browse/JDK-8260510

Maybe it is related to that change. But it is just a guess.

Hello Praveen, can you check with the submitter the exact Windows OS version and also the java vendor and version (output of "java --version" command). I haven't been able to reproduce this with a trivial jlink generated application on Windows 2019.

Additional Information from submitter:
==============================
I did some more tests and found out, that the problem is not limited to module names starting with "com".

not working:
com.project, dom.project, i.project, jdj.project, jdk.g

working:
org.project, k.project, jdl.project, jdk.i

It seems to be related to the alphabetic order. If the module name is before "jdk.httpserver", then it is not working. If the module name is after "jdk.httpserver", then it is working fine.


In addition I have tested replacing the dependency to "jdk.httpserver" with "jdk.random" or "jdk.net". But both are working fine. So it seems to be no issue with the module naming in general, but something with naming in combination with the "jdk.httpserver" module.
